dataIdInfo.idAbs: Annual Five-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for 2000 to 2025 for the national, and first- and second-order administrative division levels of Mozambique were prepared by the U.S. Census Bureau for joining (linking) to shapefiles as attribute data. The estimates are consistent with the midyear national projections from the U.S. Census Bureau International Data Base (IDB).
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The U.S. Census Bureau is providing annual subnational five-year age group population estimates by sex for Mozambique for 2000-2025 in a geographic information system (GIS) for users of the Spatial Data Repository, funded by the U.S. President’s Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR).
dataIdInfo.idCredit:
CENSUS DATA 2017 Age-Sex Data: IV Recenseamento Geral da População e Habitação 2017. Instituto Nacional de Estatistica. Third-order administrative division census age and sex data acquired from the Mozambique Instituto Nacional de Estatistica by request of USCB staff from info@ine.gov.mz on August 5, 2020.
2007 Population Total Data: III Recenseamento Geral da População e Habitação 2007, Mozambique Data Portal. Instituto Nacional de Estatistica. Available online at http://mozambique.opendataforafrica.org/puknrff/regional-statistics-of-mozambique-2015 (accessed August 25, 2020).
The U.S. Census Bureau cannot guarantee the accuracy of non-U.S. census and survey data.
GEOSPATIAL BOUNDARIES International boundaries coincide with the Large Scale International Boundaries (LSIB) dataset from the U.S. Department of State, Office of the Geographer and Global Issues. Available online at http://geonode.state.gov (accessed August 25, 2020). Geospatial data for the second-order administrative divisions of Mozambique were downloaded from the Humanitarian Data Exchange, available online at http://data.humdata.org/dataset/mozambique-administrative-levels-0-3, "moz_admbnda_adm3_ine_20190607" (accessed August 26, 2020). The U.S. Census Bureau cannot guarantee the accuracy of boundary placements.
NATIONAL ESTIMATES AND PROJECTIONS U.S. Census Bureau, Population Division. International Data Base, December 2019 release, available online at http://www.census.gov/data-tools/demo/idb/informationGateway.php, accessed August 25, 2020.

dataIdInfo.suppInfo:
SUBNATIONAL DIVISIONS Mozambique's second-order administrative divisions: 161 distritos as of the 2017 census.
SHAPEFILES The original shapefile downloaded from the Humanitarian Data Exchange had 411 polygons and matched the 2017 census postos administrativos, municípios, and distritos urbanos (third-order administrative divisions), after several changes to the subnational boundaries by USCB staff: (1) A total of 32 additional polygons were digitized by USCB staff using maps from the Instituto Nacional de Estatistica, several NGOs, and various other sources, bringing the total number of polygons to 443. These include the distritos urbanos for Cidade de Nampula, Cidade da Beira, Cidade da Matola, and Cidade de Maputo. (2) The original shapefile downloaded from the Humanitarian Data Exchange included a polygon representing the portion of Lake Malawi that falls within the national boundary of Mozambique. The shapefile also included polygons representing Chizumulu Island and Likoma Island. Although these islands are within the portion of Lake Malawi that belongs to Mozambique, they are actually part of the territory of Malawi and were removed from the original shapefile by USCB staff, bringing the total number of polygons to 441. These areas are also excluded from the official LSIB boundary for Mozambique, resulting in two "holes" in the shapefile representing those portions of Malawi territory.
These changes resulted in a shapefile with 441 polygons, one for each of Mozambique's 440 third-order administrative divisions, and one for Lake Malawi. The U.S. Census Bureau aligned the shapefile's national boundary to the Large Scale International Boundary Line (LSIB) polygon file from the U.S. Department of State, Office of the Geographer and Global Issues. Finally, the LSIB-aligned shapefile was dissolved into 162 polygons, one for each of Mozambique's 161 second-order administrative divisions (distritos) as reported by the Instituto Nacional de Estatistica in the 2017 census, and one for Lake Malawi.
CENSUS DATA INTERPOLATION The 2007 census totals had the following differences in geography that have been modified to their 2017 locations in the estimates presented here, requiring interpolation and adjustment of 2007 population data by USCB staff: (1) There were a total of 16 new postos administrativos that were formed between Mozambique's 2007 and 2017 censuses, as noted in the USCBCMNT field. Most of these new third-order administrative divisions were within newly formed distritos that had themselves been classified as postos administrativos in 2007. (2) The boundary of Cidade de Xai-Xai expanded between 2007 and 2017 to include part of Zongoene posto administrativo.
New postos administrativos, municípios, and distritos urbanos were fully formed from parts of prior single areas, and boundaries and population data were not available for the next administrative level down. The total population of the original area in 2007 was divided proportionally according to the populations of the new areas in 2017.
ADDITIONAL NOTES (1) Distritos urbanos of Cidade de Maputo are second-level administrative divisions being treated as third-level administrative divisions for the purposes of this product. (2) Population data for newly formed Barragem, Chueza, Mufa Boroma, and Malingapansi Postos Administrativos were added to their parent third-order administrative divisions by USCB staff because boundaries for these areas could not be located, as noted in the USCBCMNT field. (3) Age and sex data were available from the 2017 census for the distritos urbanos of Cidade de Lichinga, Quelimane, Cidade de Chimoio, and Cidade de Xai-Xai. Total population data from the 2007 census for the distritos urbanos of these areas were not available, however, so they were left whole by USCB staff. No distrito urbano population data were available from either census for Cidade de Pemba, Cidade de Tete, Cidade de Maxixe, and Cidade de Inhambane. (4) The original 2007 census population total reported by the Instituto Nacional de Estatistica for Molumbo distrito of 86,470 individuals was believed to be in error. It was determined that the actual 2007 population of Molumbo was likely 100,000 more than was reported, and the total was accordingly adjusted to 186,470 by USCB staff. (5) The original 2017 census 5-year age and sex data included the total population for each third-order administrative division. (6) The USCBCMNT field includes alternate names for some third-order administrative divisions.
FEATURE AND ATTRIBUTE DETAILS The 2000-2025 population estimates for Mozambique's administrative divisions are provided in the following two tables: (1) The Unicode tab-delimited text file (table) "Mozambique_5yr_age_sex_2000-2025_uscb_oct2020.txt," which can be joined to the shapefile via the common field "GEOMATCH." (2) The Excel table "Mozambique_5yr_age_sex_2000-2025_508_uscb_oct2020.xlsx," formatted for accessibility in compliance with Section 508 of the U.S. Government's Federal Rehabilitation Act.
Details on processing of the census data and calculation of 2000-2025 estimates are provided in the "Census Metadata" tab of the Excel file and "Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas" document. For the subnational areas, the U.S. Board on Geographic Names (BGN) "approved" names from the NGA GEOnet Names Server (cited in the "Credits") were used. For any area that a BGN name was not available, the name from the national census was used. Official codes for the subnational areas from the country's national statistical office, when available, are entered in the "NSO_CODE" field in both the text and Excel tables. Information on any alternative area names or recent name or boundary changes is entered in the "USCBCMNT" field. A partial list of the fields in the Excel and Unicode text files, including all fields identifying geographic names and codes, is provided in the Excel file's "Data Dictionary" tab. More detail on the U.S. Census Bureau subnational age and sex group estimates and maps for PEPFAR can be found in the document "Subnational Population Estimates Components for the Spatial Data Repository." It includes a data dictionary that is similar to that in the Excel table.
METHODOLOGY For more information, see the following methodology documents in the Spatial Data Repository: (1) "U.S. Census Bureau Methodology for SDR Subnational Population Estimates." (2) "U.S. Census Bureau Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas." (3) "Instructions for Joining Subnational Population Data to Shapefiles."
ACCESS The U.S. Census Bureau’s products for PEPFAR can be accessed from the Spatial Data Repository at http://spatialdata.dhsprogram.com/home/, which also provides access to data and maps from the DHS (Demographic and Health Surveys) Program. A zipped file containing shapefiles with metadata, an Excel workbook with subnational population estimates, and a Unicode tab-delimited text file is available for each country. PEPFAR products are also available on the Census Bureau website at http://www.census.gov/geographies/mapping-files/time-series/demo/international-programs/subnationalpopulation.html for download.
